>
  <Fragment slot="lead">
    <p class="lead">If your cups suddenly taste flat, bitter, or dusty, your grinder is usually the bottleneck. This guide shows how to clean burr coffee grinder parts fast without damaging alignment, so you get cleaner flavor and steadier extractions.</p>
  </Fragment>

  <Fragment slot="quick-answer">
    <h2 id="quick-answer">Quick answer</h2>
    <p><strong>Quick answer:</strong> Brush and wipe after each brew day, clean hopper and burr access points weekly, and deep-clean the burr chamber every 4 to 6 weeks. This reduces stale oil buildup, static cling, and grind retention that can wreck cup clarity.</p>
    <p>Think of grinder cleaning as flavor insurance: the goal is not cosmetic perfection, it is repeatable extraction. With a consistent routine, your recipes behave more predictably, your grind adjustments get smaller, and you waste fewer beans chasing problems caused by old residue.</p>
  </Fragment>

  <Fragment slot="what-youll-need">
    <h2 id="what-you-need">What you'll need before you start</h2>
    <p>You can do 90% of grinder maintenance with simple tools: a soft brush, dry cloth, and a hand blower. If your grinder has a removable burr carrier, keep a small tray nearby for screws and alignment parts. Always unplug electric grinders before opening anything. Keep a flashlight nearby too; it helps you spot fines packed in chute corners that are easy to miss under kitchen lighting.</p>
    <p>For households where espresso and pour over share one grinder, cleanup cadence matters even more. Retained fines from espresso settings can muddy filter brews, while old filter residue can flatten espresso sweetness. If you rotate brew methods often, run a tiny purge dose after major grind changes.</p>

