  <Fragment slot="steps">
    <h2 id="steps">Numbered steps: daily, weekly, monthly</h2>

    <h3>Step 1: Daily two-minute reset after brewing</h3>
    <p>When your brew session is done, run the grinder empty for one to two seconds to clear loose grounds. Pull out the catch cup, brush any compacted fines from the chute exit, and wipe the hopper lip where coffee oils build up. This tiny habit keeps old residue from contaminating your next cup.</p>
    <p>If you're dialing espresso, this step also improves repeatability. Residual fines from the previous shot can make the next one pull slower or taste harsher. A quick brush pass prevents that drift.</p>
    <p>Daily cleanup is mostly about oil control. Coffee oils oxidize quickly, especially if you brew dark roasts or keep beans in the hopper all week. Once oils oxidize, they can add papery or bitter notes even when your recipe is right. Wiping hopper surfaces and brushing the chute daily keeps those stale compounds from re-entering the next dose.</p>
    <p>It also protects your workflow speed. A grinder with heavy day-to-day buildup starts throwing inconsistent dose output, forcing you to compensate with extra purges. Two minutes now usually saves far more time later because you avoid big weekend cleanups and random dial-in resets.</p>

    <h3>Step 2: Weekly maintenance for retention and static</h3>
    <p>Once a week, empty remaining beans and remove the hopper if your model supports it. Dry-brush the upper burr area and adjustment collar, then clear the chute path with a blower. Focus on corners where fines cake up. Reinstall parts carefully and check that your usual grind reference still lands where expected.</p>
    <p>For more dial-in consistency after maintenance, pair this process with our <a href="/posts/burr-grinder-settings-for-espresso.html">burr grinder settings for espresso workflow</a>. If you mostly brew filter coffee, this cleanup method also pairs well with our <a href="/posts/coffee-brewing-ratio-guide.html">coffee brewing ratio guide</a> so flavor changes are easier to troubleshoot.</p>
    <p>Weekly cleaning is where most retention gains happen. Grounds often accumulate around anti-static tabs, chute elbows, and burr-carrier threads. These pockets slowly release old coffee into fresh doses, which causes uneven flavor and confusing extraction behavior. A weekly brush + blower routine clears those pockets before they become compacted.</p>
    <p>Take a quick photo of your grind dial before disassembly if your collar has no hard detents. That visual reference makes reassembly faster and reduces the chance of misalignment. If your grind setting shifts anyway, re-dial in with a small test brew and adjust one step at a time instead of jumping multiple clicks.</p>
    <p>For shared households, create a simple maintenance card near your grinder: daily brush, Sunday deep brush, monthly teardown date. Consistency is more important than perfection. A predictable routine beats occasional intense cleaning marathons.</p>

    <h3>Step 3: Monthly deep clean without damaging burr alignment</h3>
    <p>Every four to six weeks, do a deeper teardown according to your grinder manual. Unplug the unit, remove hopper and top burr assembly, and brush chamber walls, threads, and chute inlets thoroughly. Avoid water in the burr chamber; moisture plus fine grounds creates paste and can increase corrosion risk.</p>
    <p>After reassembly, run a sacrificial dose and discard it. Then brew a test cup and adjust grind as needed. If the grinder feels hard to stabilize after deep cleaning, you may be fighting retention-heavy hardware rather than technique. In that case, compare options in our <a href="/posts/best-burr-coffee-grinder-under-200.html">best burr grinders under $200</a> roundup.</p>
    <p>During monthly teardown, inspect burr edges for visible damage and check whether threads are collecting caked fines. You are not trying to sharpen burrs or modify alignment; you are only removing debris that interferes with predictable output. If your model includes shims or calibration rings, keep parts in order and avoid forcing anything during reassembly.</p>
    <p>After the grinder is back together, expect one to two test brews before your flavor profile fully stabilizes. Minor shifts are normal because burr positioning and retained fines changed during cleaning. Make small grind adjustments, keep brew ratio constant, and avoid changing water temperature at the same time so your diagnosis stays clean.</p>
    <p>If you regularly switch between espresso and pour over on one grinder, monthly maintenance can also reduce cross-contamination of fines between ranges. That means less muddy pour over and fewer surprise channeling issues when returning to espresso settings.</p>
  </Fragment>

  <Fragment slot="common-mistakes">
    <h2 id="mistakes">Common mistakes that make grinders dirtier faster</h2>
    <ul>
      <li><strong>Using water inside the burr chamber:</strong> it traps fines and raises rust risk over time.</li>
      <li><strong>Skipping cleanup for oily dark roasts:</strong> oil films go rancid quickly and flatten flavor.</li>
      <li><strong>Changing dose, grind, and ratio all at once:</strong> you can't tell what caused the cup to shift.</li>
      <li><strong>Forgetting calibration checks:</strong> some models need a quick zero-point verification after deep cleaning.</li>
    </ul>
    <p>Another frequent mistake is over-correcting when flavor changes after maintenance. A cleaner grinder can produce faster flow at the same dial position because fewer old fines remain in the path. That does not mean the grinder is broken. It usually means your previous setting included hidden resistance from residue.</p>
    <p>It also helps to track your brew results in a simple log for two weeks after adopting a cleaning routine. Record dose, grind mark, brew time, and a quick taste note. Patterns become obvious fast, and troubleshooting becomes objective instead of guesswork.</p>
  </Fragment>

  <Fragment slot="troubleshooting">
    <h2 id="troubleshooting">Troubleshooting after cleaning</h2>
    <ul>
      <li><strong>Shots suddenly run fast:</strong> old fines were adding resistance. Grind slightly finer and pull 1-2 calibration shots before judging flavor.</li>
      <li><strong>Filter coffee tastes hollow:</strong> check burr carrier seating and dial alignment, then return to your baseline ratio from our <a href="/posts/coffee-brewing-ratio-guide.html">coffee brewing ratio guide</a>.</li>
      <li><strong>Static mess got worse:</strong> brush anti-static tabs more thoroughly during weekly cleaning and reduce bean hopper dwell time.</li>
      <li><strong>Grind range feels shifted:</strong> verify zero-point per manual, then compare target ranges with our <a href="/posts/burr-grinder-settings-for-espresso.html">burr grinder settings guide</a>.</li>
    </ul>
  </Fragment>

